						<summary>

						

						<p>Pillar in the Sāhebu Bazaar.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Śaka 1060: 1138 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>This inscription is dated Śaka 1060 which may correspond to 1138 A.D.</p>						

						<p>It records the gift of 55 sheep on the day of Vishu-saṅkrānti for burning a perpetual lamp to the deity Trikōṭēśvaradēva by Koṇḍapa-nāyaka, son of Maṭṭe-nāyaka, for the merit of his father. The gift was left in the hands of Eṟeya-Bōya's son (name not clear) who agreed to maintain the lamp with one <hi rend="italic">māna</hi> of ghee daily.</p>						

						<p>Published in <hi rend="italic">S.I.I.,</hi> Vol. X, No. 104.</p>						

						</summary>
